      "type": "edit",
      "id": "132912aa03bef2cb",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "132912aa03bef2cb",
        "text": "**For the sake of clarity**: Our focus is not on \"scaling from below.\" Using the practice of [Emulate & Federate] is an important way to spread and apply the patterns of commoning. It enacts what we call [[intercommoning]]. Nonetheless, we regard this as a developmental way-station toward identifying recurrent \"wicked problems\" in larger, more complex, transpersonal settings -- and the commons-based governance architectures, physical infrastructures, and socio-economic systems that address them. [http://coevolving.com/blogs/index.php/archive/systems-generating-systems-architectural-design-theory-by-christopher-alexander-1968/ generative solutions] These macropatterns will help people understand that commoning has no limits. Unless we set or acquiesce to artificial limits.  \n"
      },
